      <p>medium saline
    </p></td>
  </tr>
  <tr valign=3D"TOP">=20
    <td colspan=3D"1" rowspan=3D"1" valign=3D"TOP">=20
      <p align=3D"CENTER">more than 12
    </p></td>
    <td colspan=3D"1" rowspan=3D"1" valign=3D"TOP">=20
      <p align=3D"CENTER">more than 18
    </p></td>
    <td colspan=3D"1" rowspan=3D"1" valign=3D"TOP">=20
      <p>highly saline
    </p></td>
  </tr>
</tbody></table>
</p><p></p><h2><a name=3D"7.3 crops and saline soils">7.3 Crops and saline =
soils</a></h2>
<p>Most crops do not grow well on soils that contain salts.
</p><p>One reason is that salt causes a reduction in the rate and amount of=
 water that the plant roots can take up from the soil (see Fig. 105). Also,=
 some salts are toxic to plants when present in high concentration.
</p><p align=3D"center"><b>Fig. 105. A high salt concentration in the soil =
is harmful for the plants as the water uptake is reduced</b></p><p align=3D=
"center"><img src=3D"https://www.fao.org/4/r4082e/r4082e43.gif">
</p><p>Some plants are more tolerant to a high salt concentration than othe=
rs. Some examples are given in the following table:
</p><p><table border=3D""><tbody><tr valign=3D"TOP"><td colspan=3D"1" rowsp=
an=3D"1" valign=3D"TOP">
<p align=3D"CENTER"><b>Highly tolerant</b></p></td><td colspan=3D"1" rowspa=
n=3D"1" valign=3D"TOP">
